$ oc create user mike

$ oc create identity allow_all:mike                      //allow_all is a identity provider name, other names would be ldap, github, HTPasswd etc.

$ oc create useridentitymapping allow_all:mike   

Normally, OpenShift creates the Identity, User, and the mapping automatically when a user logs in through an Identity Provider. You only manually create them separately for testing, 
troubleshooting, or special cases.

$ oc delete user mike


service account: 
have direct access to APIs
should be created for a specific job, otherwise the default service account which is like a cluster admin would get used
$ oc create sa mikesa
$ oc get sa
$ oc policy add-role-to-user view system: serviceaccount: sockshop: mikesa           //it gives view only permission for the sa 'mikesa' over the 'sockshop' project                    
$ oc policy add-role-to-group view system: serviceaccount sockshop -n sockshop       //it adds view only permission to the sockshop namespace via a group
$ oc adm groups new mikesgroup mike michelle                                         //oc adm groups: command; new: flag
$ oc get groups


RBAC:
a role needs to be binding to a user or a service account, we assign permmissions to roles

ConfigMap:
a key-value pair 

Secrets:
by default Kubernetes uses OPAC standard which stores the secret in plain text, that's the reason that Kubernetes secrets are recoomanded in real world

SCC (Security Context Constraints):
you would see this in deployment yaml files:
SecurityContext:
  privileged: true                  
by default privileged: false, 'true' allows a container to run with almost the same privileges as the host's root user
rivileged access would be required to access some system components like CNI plugins (Calico, Flannel, etc.), CSI storage drivers etc.
